=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Welcome back to The Best &amp; The Brighte=
st. I=E2=80=99m <strong>Abby
Livingston</strong>.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Flags are at half-staff across the=
 country today to honor the life of <strong>Jimmy Carter</strong>, the oft-=
maligned one-term president who became a Nobel Peace Prize-winning humanita=
rian and diplomat after leaving the White House. (Somewhat unfairly blamed =
for the Iran hostage crisis, Carter is now one of the most popular ex-presi=
dents in history.) There=E2=80=99s a poignancy to the timing
of his passing, with memorial services=E2=80=94scheduled for January 8 at t=
he National Cathedral=E2=80=94taking place just as <strong>Joe Biden</stron=
g>, a young first-term senator at the time of Carter=E2=80=99s election to =
the presidency, departs the office.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0=
px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Of course, these gatherings always ma=
ke for intriguing people-watching (and =E2=80=9Cpower mourning,=E2=80=9D as=
 <strong>Mark Leibovich</strong> once wryly observed), especially when the =
capital=E2=80=99s high
church hosts the ex-presidents club. Whether or not <strong>Donald Trump</s=
trong> will be invited, or will attend, the once-and-future president relea=
sed a gracious pair of statements, calling Carter =E2=80=9Ca truly good man=
=2E=E2=80=9D One hopes this tactfulness will last.=C2=A0</p></div>
