=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">But there are logistical obstacles to earl=
y resignation.
Granger, for example, is said to have felt up to the job at the beginning o=
f a term, but found herself declining midway through. She was hoping to fin=
ish her term with a minimum of business on Capitol Hill, and was prepared t=
o return to D.C. as needed, according to a Granger source. And while her di=
strict office had mostly closed up shop=E2=80=94a detail that was sensation=
alized by the Dallas Express=E2=80=94that=E2=80=99s standard operating proc=
edure for retiring members. In brutal fashion, members are evicted from
their offices as soon as the election is over=E2=80=94sometimes sooner. (Th=
e government tries to get members out of their district office space by the=
 end of their term on January 3, to avoid taxpayers having to cover unneces=
sary rent. )</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;">Sure, Granger could have resigned early, in the spirit of tr=
ansparency=E2=80=94and maybe she should have. But Congressman-elect <strong=
>Craig Goldman</strong>, her successor, wouldn=E2=80=99t have
been appointed in her place. In Texas, as in most states, <a href=3D"https:=
//email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dVR3FrOGZqL=
U9aTEhLVFRlaDVoND0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9zdGF0dXRlcy5jYXBpdG9sLnRleGFzLmdv=
